extends ./subSubTemplate.jade

block subSubTitle
	h1
		b Calculating eigenvalues and eigenvectors using the characteristic polynomial

block subSubContent
	h3
		b Introduction
	p The characteristic polynomial of a matrix is a polynomial whose roots are the eigenvalues of the matrix.
	p We know from the definition of eigenvalues and eigenvectors that:
	p $$Av=\lambda v$$
	p Note that
	p $$Av-\lambda v=0$$
	p $$Av-\lambda Iv=0$$
	p $$(A-\lambda I)v=0$$
	p Trivially we see that \(v=0\) is a solution.
	p Otherwise matrix \(A-\lambda I\) must be non-invertible. That is:
	p $$Det(A-\lambda I)=0$$
	h3
		b Calculating eigenvalues
	p For example
	p $$A=\begin{bmatrix}2&1\\1 & 2\end{bmatrix}$$
	p $$A-\lambda I=\begin{bmatrix}2-\lambda &1\\1 & 2-\lambda \end{bmatrix}$$
	p $$Det(A-\lambda I)=(2-\lambda )(2-\lambda )-1$$
	p When this is \(0\).
	p $$(2-\lambda )(2-\lambda )-1=0$$
	p $$\lambda =1,3$$
	h3
		b Calculating eigenvectors
	p You can plug this into the original problem.
	p For example
	p $$Av=3v$$
	p $$\begin{bmatrix}2&1\\1 & 2\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}x_1\\x_2\end{bmatrix}=3\begin{bmatrix}x_1\\x_2\end{bmatrix}$$
	p As vectors can be defined at any point on the line, we normalise \(x_1=1\).
	p $$\begin{bmatrix}2&1\\1 & 2\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}1\\x_2\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}3\\3x_2\end{bmatrix}$$
	p Here \(x_2=1\) and so the eigenvector corresponding to eigenvalue \(3\) is:
	p $$\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\end{bmatrix}$$
	
